-scaling: it adapts to the needs of the developer, from simple scripts to complex systems. The language emphasizes clarity through postfix operators, eliminating precedence rules, and optional region-based memory management.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb330\s2\sl413 {\*\bkmkstart ID_intro_45_philosophy}{\*\bkmkend ID_intro_45_philosophy}\b\fs31\lang1024\f1 1.2 Design Philosophy\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\sl286 \b0\fs22\lang1033\f0 Scaly follows these core principles:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \fs17\lang1024 \'95 \i\fs22 Clarity over cleverness\i0  \'97 Code should be readable without mental parsing of operator precedence.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \fs17 \'95 \i\fs22 Explicit over implicit\i0  \'97 Memory management and control flow are visible in the code structure.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \fs17 \'95 \i\fs22 Incremental complexity\i0  \'97 Simple programs stay simple; advanced features are available when needed.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb330\s2\sl413 {\*\bkmkstart ID_intro_45_status}{\*\bkmkend ID_intro_45_status}\b\fs31\f1 1.3 Implementation Status\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\sl286 \b0\fs22\lang1033\f0 This specification documents the language as it is implemented. Features are added incrementally, with each addition reflected immediately in this document.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\sl286 Current implementation status:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \fs17\lang1024 \'95 \fs22 Literals \'97 \i implemented\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \i0\fs17 \'95 \fs22 Operators \'97 \i planned\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \i0\fs17 \'95 \fs22 Bindings \'97 \i planned\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \i0\fs17 \'95 \fs22 Functions \'97 \i planned\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb330\s1\sl466 {\*\bkmkstart ID_lexical}{\*\bkmkend ID_lexical}\b\i0\fs35\f1 2 Lexical Structure\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb330\s2\sl413 {\*\bkmkstart ID_lex_45_overview}{\*\bkmkend ID_lex_45_overview}\fs31 2.1 Overview\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\sl286 \b0\fs22\lang1033\f0 This chapter describes the lexical structure of Scaly: how source text is divided into tokens. The lexer transforms a sequence of characters into a sequence of tokens that the parser then processes.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb330\s2\sl413 {\*\bkmkstart ID_lex_45_whitespace}{\*\bkmkend ID_lex_45_whitespace}\b\fs31\lang1024\f1 2.2 Whitespace and Line Breaks\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\sl286 \b0\fs22\lang1033\f0 Whitespace characters (space, tab) separate tokens but are otherwise insignificant. Line breaks, however, are syntactically meaningful in Scaly \'97 they can terminate statements and declarations.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\sl286 A colon (\f2 :\f0 ) can be used in place of a line break when multiple statements should appear on a single line.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb330\s2\sl413 {\*\bkmkstart ID_lex_45_comments}{\*\bkmkend ID_lex_45_comments}\b\fs31\lang1024\f1 2.3 Comments\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\sl286 \b0\fs22\lang1033\f0 Scaly supports two forms of comments:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \fs17\lang1024 \'95 \i\fs22 Single-line comments\i0  start with a semicolon (\f2 ;\f0 ) and extend to the end of the line.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb165\li286\sl286\fi-286 \fs17 \'95 \i\fs22 Multi-line comments\i0  start with \f2 ;*\f0  and end with \f2 *;\f0 .\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb330\sl257 \fs19\f2 \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
